The paper deals with game theory and cryptography, which are both subfields of computer science. The focus is on defining solution concepts for computationally bounded players in a fixed finite game, which falls under the category of game theory (cs.GT). The paper also discusses the use of cryptographic protocols to represent abstract games, which relates to the subfield of cryptography (cs.CR). Additionally, the paper mentions the use of computational complexity theory to analyze the strategic behavior of players, which falls under the categories of information theory (cs.IT) and computational complexity (cs.CC). Finally, the paper proposes a computational version of Nash equilibrium and sequential equilibrium, which relates to the subfield of artificial intelligence (cs.AI).
